title: For Sale:  HK MP5 Navy clone
postcontent:
Greetings all-I have a semi-automatic MP5 clone for sale. 

This weapon began life as an HK factory German MP5 Navy submachine gun. I have photographs of the complete machine gun prior to me personally de-milling it per ATF specifications. A true navy gun is marked MP5N on the top of the receiver, threaded barrel, tritium front and rear sights, and an ambidextrous safe/semi/full pictograph lower. 

I then had a local FFL purchase a bare, semi auto/shelf receiver from Black Market Parts in Arizona. The receiver is marked, "Special Weapons, Spring Lakes, MI."

I then gave the receiver and Navy parts set to MOJO Tactical in southern Missouri. The owner is a professional TIG welder by trade, and the completed pistol returned absolutely beautiful--semi of course, new in appearance, and exceeding all expectations. It is of course, 922r compliant.

The pistol has a flapper mag release, SIG arm brace, Sure Fire 628 LM LED forearm, and it comes with one HK german factory magazine and HK factory 3 point sling  

The HK German MP5 Navy donor gun was originally owned by a California Police Department. It appeared near new when I got it-but it is a used gun, and as such, the  parts in this gun are not brand new. 

Parts value-An HK MP5 navy parts set costs around $2500. A receiver flat and the weld up parts costs around $175. The metal butt cap, tube, and SIG arm brace cost around $300.  The Surefire 628 LM LED pressure/switch light costs $350.00. Actual fair cost for the parts is approximately $3325.00. 

Build cost-This varies from the person involved, but quality work to do it all (receiver, parts conversion, flapper mag, and finish) is in the $1400 range. 

As outlined above, this is around a $4500.00 pistol.   



The build cost varies, based on who you use, but $1000 would be a conservative amount. Total for the parts and build work

title: For Sale:  Eddystone M1917
postcontent:
Eddystone M1917 $615

 Excellent bore and rifling, Muzzle erosion 1.5!

 The bad: Import marked, missing screw on rear sling swivel, no stacking ring.

 This rifle has some real history to it!

 WWI service
 WWII service in Canada
 Post war service in Denmark!

 Now back home!

 Eddystone 1917 went to Canada for WWII as seen on the receiver and butt stock (RCOC = Royal Canadian Ordnance Corps.)

 Then sold to Denmark for Home Guard use. So it is Import marked on the barrel. Still has a decent amount of the original blued finish after all that. Stock is in good shape couple of dings but nice coloring to it.

 Denmark made several adjustments to the rifle, the magazine follower is filed down so the bolt does not hang up on the last round. Also added a Danish front sight post.

 Bore is very nice with some shine and great rifling. Original Barrel "E" 7/18. It is an excellent shooter.

 Most parts are "E" marked except the hand guard (R) one part on the bolt has a (W) and Rear sight is marked (R). Rest I can see are Eddystone made.

title: For Sale:  S&W 915
location: Uptown / W. Suburbs, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
Classic Smith & Wesson Model 915. This was S&W's "Value-Edition" pistol immediately prior to the federal assault weapons ban. Very similar to the S&W Model 5903, it is an all-metal gun with a steel slide and alloy frame. 

Contrary to some information online, all parts other than the grip are metal. Later "Value-Edition" models like the 910 used polymer material for the guide rods and sights; not this Model 915. It differs primarily from the Model 5903 by having an easier-to-machine frame and lacking ambidextrous controls. Most parts, including magazines, grips, springs and barrels are interchangeable with the 59xx series.

This is an astoundingly reliable handgun that in my ownership of approximately 1 year has never had a single failure. I purchased this pistol one year ago and replaced the springs with a high-quality set from Wolfe and replaced the grips with a singe-piece Hogue soft rubber. All 3 magazines are extremely dependable Mec-Gar with a 15-round capacity.

All 3 magazines and case are included in price. Ammo not included.

Please respond via Armslist email or directly to BigMorgan612 (at) gmail (dot) com

title: For Sale:  FFL Transfer Service For Your Online or Auction Purchases
postcontent:
Rates and Policies

Firearm Transfer Fee is $15 for 1st transaction, each additional firearm is $10
Transfers for Law Enforcement, Fire Fighters (active or retired) is $10
We accept Visa, Mastercard, Discover, Cash, Money Orders
You should contact us prior to and after purchasing if having a firearm shipped to us.​

Transfer Infomation for local Idaho Customers
Incoming Transfers from a FFL dealer:  We are already listed with most online retailers on their FFL listings, If not I will need to know how they accept a copy of my FFL licence usually either through fax or email, although some dealers require a hardcopy mailed to them. After I send a copy of my FFL licence to the dealer they will ship the firearm to me, I require that the shipping dealer include a copy of their FFL licence and your contact information with the shipment. When the firearm arrives I will contact you and you will need to come to my office to fill out the paperwork.The process is simple, you come in fill out the ATF 4473, present your picture ID or carry permit and I handle all the paperwork, do all the checks required and get you on your way. Generally this process takes no longer than 15 munutes. 

If Purchasing from an Individual
I will send the individual an email with the first 3 and the last 5 digits of my FFL licence, and a link to the ATF web site to verify my shipping address. I will also need the individual to send me a copy of their drivers licence (which must have a physical address on it, no PO boxes). When the firearm arrives I will contact you and you will need to come to my office to fill out the paperwork so we can transfer the firearm to you.
​
Outgoing Transfers
If you have sold a firearm that needs to be shipped out of state it can only be shipped to an FFL. I will need a copy of the FFL's licence, and what type of firearm you are shipping. We generally have shipping boxes for Handguns available at no extra charge, for Long guns you may need to provide a box or there will be a small extra charge for us to buy a box for you.

Important Note on Outgoing Transfers
In the case of firearms shipments there is no law that prevents an individual from shipping a firearm to an FFL holder. Some FFL's do not accept shipments from individuals (We Do), and handguns need to be shipped next day air through shipping companies. The fact that as an FFL we can ship handguns through the USPS, it is sometimes cheaper for you to pay our transfer fee plus the shipping then to ship it yourself. There will also be times where it might be cheaper for you to ship a firearm to an FFL yourself. It depends on the type of firearm, and the distance it is traveling.
Just remember you can only ship a firearm to a Federal Firearms Licensee. When in doubt check the laws or give us a call and we will try to assist you.

Any questions or inquires please feel free to call or email us.

REDACTED
​REDACTED
​Star, Idaho 83669
